00:18:42.920 --> 00:18:50.520
Something I know we were talking about a little bit earlier in preparing for this week, is you

00:18:50.520 --> 00:18:55.160
talked a little bit about how you drive and stir empirical thinking with your teams and

00:18:55.160 --> 00:19:00.040
marketing stakeholders. And I remember Googling like what that actually meant and now I don't

00:19:00.040 --> 00:19:07.560
remember. So can you tell me a little bit about that? Yeah, so I was working and so when I was

00:19:08.040 --> 00:19:13.479
working at Domino's, this is probably back in 2018, I went to this conference called the ARF or

00:19:13.479 --> 00:19:18.439
Advertising Research Foundation. And it's just a conference for people that work in the advertising

00:19:18.439 --> 00:19:24.040
or marketing space, whether that's advertisers themselves or brand marketers or data scientists

00:19:24.040 --> 00:19:31.479
to get together to kind of talk to best practices. And the keynote in that conference, the speaker

00:19:31.880 --> 00:19:38.119
the speaker said, I want you all to take away one thing today and that's to go back to your

00:19:38.119 --> 00:19:42.839
workplace and foment empiricism. And at the time, I didn't really understand what that meant. And

00:19:42.839 --> 00:19:46.920
then as I continued to kind of sit on that a little bit and let it marinate, I really thought

00:19:46.920 --> 00:19:52.680
about it. And because generally, foment has a very negative connotation, which is kind of like, I'm

00:19:52.680 --> 00:19:58.920
going to stir up and like cause some trouble. But if you consider fomenting empiricism, it's like

00:19:59.560 --> 00:20:03.160
within whatever workplace you're in or whatever setting you're in,

00:20:03.160 --> 00:20:09.079
just driving the thinking of having data and empirical evidence to support your decision

00:20:09.079 --> 00:20:13.239
making. I think it really goes a long way for, as I'm talking to my team or talking to our business

00:20:13.239 --> 00:20:19.319
stakeholders to think through, we may have a gut feeling about something, but how can we think a

00:20:19.319 --> 00:20:24.199
little more analytically minded and try to challenge ourselves to see what the data would show

00:20:24.199 --> 00:20:29.239
us and try to drive a bit more value in terms of what's capable there, rather than kind of just

00:20:29.239 --> 00:20:36.520
taking things status quo. I'm guessing that's what you're referring to. Yes, that is. But I'm

00:20:36.520 --> 00:20:43.719
curious if there's like a time that comes to mind that your team did that or project for that helped

00:20:43.719 --> 00:20:49.160
the outcomes. Yeah, I think generally it's more of a mentality that I try to push with my team,

00:20:49.160 --> 00:20:56.359
especially as we get requests from stakeholders. So one thing is I try to push an embedded nature,

00:20:56.359 --> 00:21:01.239
especially within the analytics team. The data scientists team are more focused on like a project

00:21:01.239 --> 00:21:07.000
basis. The analysts are really embedded within the teams that we're working with. So this could

00:21:07.000 --> 00:21:12.119
range from brand media, social media, content, SEO, CRM, performance marketing. We work with a lot of

00:21:12.119 --> 00:21:16.920
different marketing departments and the analysts are basically aligned to some of these different

00:21:16.920 --> 00:21:22.920
aspects to really be embedded within those cultures and not just an outsider kind of

00:21:22.920 --> 00:21:28.280
looking in to try to get context after the fact when they have a question. So as they're embedded,

00:21:28.280 --> 00:21:34.760
it allows for us to think as a team rather than say, hey, I'm a marketer. Hey, data team, I have this

00:21:34.760 --> 00:21:40.760
problem. Can you solve it for me? It's more, this is a problem that we have as a company.

00:21:40.760 --> 00:21:45.800
Now, how can we think together to better ideate this overall business problem? So the analysts

00:21:45.800 --> 00:21:51.479
really have a seat at the table to have a lot of that ideation to identify that we even have a

00:21:51.479 --> 00:21:57.079
business problem to begin with and then take that business problem and translate it now ourselves

00:21:57.079 --> 00:22:01.319
as the data team into a data problem and then build a data solution to solve that problem.

00:22:01.319 --> 00:22:06.680
But I think a lot of it is just coming back to having this mindset of making sure that we're

00:22:06.680 --> 00:22:11.319
keeping focused on the end goal that we're looking for and not necessarily say, hey, data team,

00:22:11.319 --> 00:22:16.040
can you go pull this data for us? The gut reaction is, sure, I can easily do that for you,

00:22:16.040 --> 00:22:19.719
but what's the intent of the question that you're trying to solve or the problem that you're trying

00:22:19.719 --> 00:22:25.319
to solve? And let us think a bit more holistically and as a partnership so we can think to try to

00:22:25.319 --> 00:22:30.599
drive a bit more solutioning and decisioning behind that because we, as data science and analytics,

00:22:31.239 --> 00:22:35.479
already have that mindset and know a bit more of what data can do. The stakeholders,

00:22:35.479 --> 00:22:41.959
even though they are very focused in having data drive their organization, they don't

00:22:41.959 --> 00:22:45.319
necessarily know what data can do. They know how they would want to analyze data, but it's not

00:22:45.319 --> 00:22:50.040
necessarily the right way. So to kind of come back to your question, Rachel, about a specific

00:22:50.040 --> 00:22:56.359
instance, we received one question early on from one of our stakeholders when I came here,

00:22:56.359 --> 00:23:01.719
and it was, hey, can you go do a segmentation for us or can you build some clusters for us?

00:23:02.439 --> 00:23:07.719
And when he's like, I mean, yeah, we could, but what are the hypotheses that you have that you're

00:23:07.719 --> 00:23:10.839
trying to solve? What is the business problem you're trying to solve? And I didn't really have

00:23:10.839 --> 00:23:14.920
the context of the business at the time because I was only about a month in, but it really comes

00:23:14.920 --> 00:23:19.719
back to trying to identify what is it you're trying to solve out of this? If I deliver some segments

00:23:19.719 --> 00:23:24.199
for you, how are you going to use that to drive decisions? Are you going to have personalization?

00:23:24.199 --> 00:23:28.439
Is it going to change your audience strategy? Is it going to allow us to do some type of testing

00:23:28.439 --> 00:23:32.520
to make sure they're relevant? So I think just continuing to have those conversations with

00:23:32.520 --> 00:23:37.000
stakeholders allows it to be a bit more focused and less prescriptive from their part, and more

00:23:37.000 --> 00:23:45.319
so thinking a bit more generally about what can be done. We were actually just talking about that a

00:23:45.319 --> 00:23:52.439
bit internally this week and thinking about the problem first before we start jumping into all

00:23:52.439 --> 00:23:59.400
these different solutions. But part of that was also like getting everybody to agree on what

00:23:59.400 --> 00:24:06.520
the problem is. Is that something you have to do across all teams? Yeah, it's definitely something

00:24:06.520 --> 00:24:12.040
we have to do. I think it's a bit easier when you take it back in terms of prioritization,

00:24:12.040 --> 00:24:18.359
because we kind of know as a company what our goal is over the next five years. And we all,

00:24:18.359 --> 00:24:21.959
as we're doing our own objective setting, we're making sure that they kind of align up to that.

00:24:22.439 --> 00:24:30.760
So if we receive a question about, like, hey, can we do this analysis to see what's going to happen

00:24:30.760 --> 00:24:36.920
here? Whether that's like an analysis for which marketing campaign worked better or which specific

00:24:36.920 --> 00:24:45.239
channel on a specific campaign drove the most XYZ aspect within our brand. It kind of comes down to

00:24:45.239 --> 00:24:51.319
how is this going to help us align towards us reaching our goal? Because there's a significant

00:24:51.319 --> 00:24:55.400
amount of questions that we ourselves are asking ourselves, that our marketing team is asking,

00:24:55.400 --> 00:25:00.359
that our product team is asking, our operation team is asking. And there's a lot more questions

00:25:00.359 --> 00:25:05.319
than there are resources within the team. So it really comes down to having a very level head in

00:25:05.319 --> 00:25:10.040
terms of prioritization to make sure that we're focused on the right problems. And then if we

00:25:10.040 --> 00:25:16.520
can't align on there being a problem in itself, then I think that's one of those general things

00:25:16.520 --> 00:25:21.000
where it's, let's kind of think through what are some of our hypotheses and then continue to refine

00:25:21.239 --> 00:25:25.560
about what it is we're trying to get out of this. Sometimes that's just relevant for an

00:25:25.560 --> 00:25:29.319
exploration exercise to say, do we really have a problem or do we kind of just think there is?

00:25:31.719 --> 00:25:35.160
Thank you. Anas, I see you have your hand raised. Do you want to jump in here?

00:25:36.599 --> 00:25:43.239
Sure. Josh, so I want to pick your brain on, I'm assuming that your company does use social

00:25:43.239 --> 00:25:50.760
media data to find prospective customers. And I'm just curious of, obviously, whatever you can share,

00:25:51.640 --> 00:25:59.479
if you use any other tools in that process, whether to feed into a model or, I don't know,

00:25:59.479 --> 00:26:05.000
that's a personal interest of mine, leveraging social media data and incorporating it into a

00:26:05.000 --> 00:26:12.839
model. So, yeah, so I think there's a couple of different aspects there. One is generally within

00:26:13.479 --> 00:26:21.239
the newer privacy constraints, it's hard to do any type of user-level analysis where you

00:26:21.239 --> 00:26:25.959
necessarily know specifically, especially within social media, any actions that a user is taking,

00:26:25.959 --> 00:26:29.160
and then align, especially if you want to align that to something that's happening within our

00:26:29.160 --> 00:26:36.119
platform. So that's one aspect. As an aside, I'm somewhat generally for sharing my data,

00:26:36.119 --> 00:26:42.199
because as a data scientist and as a marketing-focused data scientist, I prefer to have

00:26:42.199 --> 00:26:46.359
ads that are 100% relevant to me so that I don't have to go searching for something else. I just,

00:26:46.359 --> 00:26:52.760
like, every single ad that I receive is something that I want or would need. So that's an aside.

00:26:53.479 --> 00:27:00.359
The other aspect there is getting into, like, using social media data. So one specific aspect

00:27:00.359 --> 00:27:05.239
that you could utilize there, and this is, like, under the assumption that maybe you're working

00:27:05.239 --> 00:27:13.239
for a brand and you have some means of aligning on driving relevant people to whatever platform

00:27:13.239 --> 00:27:20.040
you may have, is by using signals that you can send back to things like Google or Facebook that

00:27:20.040 --> 00:27:26.439
allow them on their end to do some type of, like, look-alike audience building, where it's, like,

00:27:26.439 --> 00:27:32.199
hey, I've received these thousand people from your platform, and here's the click that they

00:27:32.199 --> 00:27:37.400
came into our site on. I don't necessarily know who they are, but I can say, like, this is the

00:27:37.400 --> 00:27:43.640
value that we see based on some predictive model we've built, and then send that value back to those

00:27:43.640 --> 00:27:48.280
social media channels so that they can, therefore, say, okay, I know how much you spent on this click.

00:27:48.280 --> 00:27:52.359
I know the value that your receiver met. Now I can help optimize the return on that spend that

00:27:52.359 --> 00:27:56.119
you're giving us to send more relevant customers back to you, and they can do that via look-alike

00:27:56.119 --> 00:28:07.400
audience modeling. Cool. Thank you. Yeah, sure. There was actually a follow-up question that was

00:28:07.400 --> 00:28:14.359
asked, well, maybe not a follow-up. It was asked anonymously earlier, but have the recent privacy

00:28:14.359 --> 00:28:22.040
changes in browsers affected your MTA modeling if you do this? And I might need to know what MTA is

00:28:22.839 --> 00:28:29.640
and push your efforts forward and then. Yeah, so MTA stands for multi-touch attribution,

00:28:29.640 --> 00:28:34.920
which is a means of aligning all of the marketing touch points that a user could have before they

00:28:34.920 --> 00:28:39.959
make some action or they don't make an action. And so, yes, definitely privacy constraints are a

00:28:39.959 --> 00:28:44.760
significant blocker there. Even thinking back to, like, 2018 when we were doing this at Domino's,

00:28:44.760 --> 00:28:49.000
it was a significant blocker within the social media channels specifically that are very

00:28:49.000 --> 00:28:53.959
walled gardens. You can't align on an impression level basis who's seeing your ads. So it's

00:28:53.959 --> 00:28:59.079
definitely a challenge there. One way that we're trying to work around that is by rather than

00:28:59.079 --> 00:29:04.280
building out a pure, what I would call MTA, which is generally using some type of Markov chain model

00:29:05.000 --> 00:29:09.719
that is impression level, that we're building out more of a click-based MTA, which aligns

00:29:09.719 --> 00:29:14.119
for a specific user. Again, this kind of comes down to our identity resolution and how well we

00:29:14.119 --> 00:29:19.079
can align any specific click to any specific individual for any of the clicks that they're

00:29:19.079 --> 00:29:23.800
making. What is the allocation that we may give to each of the marketing touch points that they have

00:29:23.800 --> 00:29:29.239
before they make some action? So that allows us to get a bit more perspective into some, what you

00:29:29.239 --> 00:29:33.719
may call, like, supporting marketing channels rather than, say, the last click before an action

00:29:33.719 --> 00:29:37.319
happens or the first click before an action happens. So you can kind of consider some

00:29:37.319 --> 00:29:41.719
different weighting scenarios there that may do it. The other aspect there was getting into the

00:29:41.719 --> 00:29:47.000
MMM. And this is kind of like, I'd say, over the last four or five years, there's been a bit of a

00:29:47.000 --> 00:29:53.319
resurgence in an MMM where prior to that, everybody was saying, oh, MMM's dead. It's such an archaic

00:29:53.319 --> 00:29:57.479
method that's being utilized to optimize marketing spend. And like, yeah, it was developed in the

00:29:57.479 --> 00:30:02.119
60s, but it's still highly relevant, especially now as privacy concerns are coming out, especially

00:30:02.119 --> 00:30:07.479
within Europe where privacy laws are already well ahead of what they are in the U.S. So the benefit

00:30:07.479 --> 00:30:12.599
to an MMM is that it doesn't require user-level data to do this. It's very looking at it from

00:30:12.599 --> 00:30:17.800
econometrics perspective and building out a model that can be very focused across the entirety and

00:30:17.800 --> 00:30:23.160
not just within digital channels, also within, like, TV and terrestrial radio and billboards

00:30:23.160 --> 00:30:25.640
to get a read into how all the marketing channels kind of work together.

00:30:29.319 --> 00:30:32.280
Thank you. Martin, I see you have your hand raised. Nice to see you.

00:30:33.160 --> 00:30:38.680
Nice to see you, Rachel. Hi, I'm Martin. I'm the CMO at union.ai. We do

00:30:41.160 --> 00:30:46.119
data and ML orchestrators. I used to work for our studio, so I know some people here.

00:30:48.680 --> 00:30:52.280
So I think this is super interesting. I asked the last question, Josh, MTA versus

00:30:52.839 --> 00:31:00.520
a market chain-based MTAs and so on. But I see also the resurgence of MMM, but it has issues,

00:31:00.520 --> 00:31:07.400
right? I mean, if you have, like, time series that are short or sparsity of observations,

00:31:07.400 --> 00:31:09.479
it's not going to be good. So how do you overcome that?

00:31:10.119 --> 00:31:12.760
Yeah, it's definitely a challenge you have to kind of work with.

00:31:15.560 --> 00:31:19.719
One potential method, which, like, granted, it's not necessarily going to always be relevant,

00:31:19.719 --> 00:31:24.839
but if you're able to go further in granularity, then that can start to improve some of the sample

00:31:24.839 --> 00:31:29.400
size you have available in order to build out a model and allows you to do a bit more robust

00:31:29.400 --> 00:31:36.439
techniques. So right now, the model that we're building is, one, it's using open source framework

00:31:36.439 --> 00:31:41.479
from Facebook called Robin, which is pretty powerful, and it's built in R, and it's pretty

00:31:41.479 --> 00:31:47.319
out-of-the-box capable of doing pretty robust MMMs. Next steps beyond that are getting into

00:31:47.319 --> 00:31:52.040
more, when you think of, like, rigorously focused ones, getting into a hierarchical time series

00:31:52.040 --> 00:31:57.560
using Bayesian methods, which there's a package in R called rstan, which uses the stan framework to

00:31:57.560 --> 00:32:03.560
get into that Bayesian level. That's where we use the dominoes. And within that, as you continue

00:32:03.560 --> 00:32:09.719
to increase the levels of granularity, you can use the posterior distribution from one model

00:32:09.719 --> 00:32:13.640
to inform the priors, getting into another one, which allows you to kind of account for some of

00:32:13.640 --> 00:32:21.239
that sparsity you may have just by getting through there. Another means is by, if you don't want to

00:32:21.239 --> 00:32:25.479
go further in granularity, you can actually do the opposite and start to aggregate some of those

00:32:25.479 --> 00:32:29.800
marketing channels that may be relevant from a consumer's perspective. So one of the considerations

00:32:29.800 --> 00:32:36.680
we made with the current model that we're focusing on at TKWW is by aggregating Pinterest and Instagram,

00:32:36.680 --> 00:32:42.119
which, like, they're completely different marketing channels, and they have, like, meta and

00:32:42.119 --> 00:32:47.560
Pinterest have no combination to each other, but from a consumer perspective, when they're considering

00:32:47.560 --> 00:32:51.719
wedding planning, they're both used as a means of getting visual inspiration for planning their

00:32:51.719 --> 00:32:56.520
wedding and seeing photos that are relevant to search for. So it makes sense to aggregate

00:32:56.520 --> 00:33:00.680
both of those together because of the sparsity that we had in some of those channels, which allows us

00:33:00.680 --> 00:33:05.079
to get a good insight to say, we may not be able to see what Pinterest is doing or what

00:33:05.079 --> 00:33:09.239
Instagram is doing in a silo, but we can say for visual inspiration, it has this return on our ad

00:33:09.239 --> 00:33:15.719
spend. And then as we get into further models later on, then you can get into that hierarchical

00:33:15.719 --> 00:33:19.160
analysis where you're able to then parse down what's actually happening within each of those

00:33:19.160 --> 00:33:28.920
channels specifically. Thanks. Caitlin, I see you had a question in the chat a bit earlier, too,

00:33:28.920 --> 00:33:38.359
if you want to jump in next. I can get started with the question, but it was,

00:33:39.479 --> 00:33:43.319
how do you collaborate between R and Python? Are these separate teams?

00:33:44.199 --> 00:33:49.959
They're not separate teams. It kind of depends on what people are used to using. And that's

00:33:49.959 --> 00:33:56.359
definitely a struggle to consider when you want to do quality assurance on the code basis,

00:33:56.359 --> 00:34:00.599
but that's being written. If one of the data scientists is an expert in the problem that

00:34:00.599 --> 00:34:05.719
you're trying to solve or has some knowledge about it, but they know Python and I'm coding in R,

00:34:05.719 --> 00:34:10.919
then it definitely becomes a challenge. We're currently working on building out our overall

00:34:11.560 --> 00:34:17.479
data roadmap for our department on what is the appropriate means and scenario here for getting

00:34:17.479 --> 00:34:24.600
it and being able to have this cross-code capabilities. I think one of the challenges

00:34:24.600 --> 00:34:31.320
there is, again, if you're focused on a specific language, you're not necessarily focused on the

00:34:31.320 --> 00:34:37.479
problem itself, which you can also relate to if you're focused on, hey, I just found this new

00:34:37.479 --> 00:34:41.800
novel technique. Let me see how I can pigeonhole it into the problem that I have. Then you're not

00:34:41.800 --> 00:34:47.159
really focused on the problem because that may not be as relevant. So I think one of the areas to do

00:34:47.159 --> 00:34:54.040
is just have some means of identifying who would be relevant to look at your code base, even if

00:34:54.040 --> 00:34:58.679
they're not necessarily on the same team. I've been at some companies in the past that were

00:34:58.679 --> 00:35:04.040
significant in size where there was basically an internal R user group and an internal Python user

00:35:04.040 --> 00:35:08.919
group, which allows for a lot of that language-specific collaboration and discussions.

